ce more to questions of literary form and technique, the kinds of writings considered in this collection - writings that were immensely popular in their own time - have not attracted the same amount of attention as more secular forms. The collection as a whole offers new insights for scholars interested in form, style, poetics, literary history and aesthetics, by considering sanctity first and foremost as literature  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aEnglish literaturexHistory and criticismxMiddle English, 1100-1500. 0aEnglish literatureyMiddle English, 1100-1500xHistory and criticism. 0aReligion in literature. 0aSaints in literaturexCriticism, interpretation, etc. 0aSaints in literature. 4aLiterature Studies 2020. 4aMedieval Studies 2020. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh  aBritish Isles.  aSanctity.  aliterariness.  amedieval literature.  apoetics.1 aAsh, Kate, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAtkin, Tamara, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBarr, Jessica, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBernau, Anke, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBernau, Anke, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aFulton, Helen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGreenspan, Kate, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJames, Sarah, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLynch, Andrew, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSanok, Catherine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSiebach Larsen, Anna, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSisk, Jennifer L., econtributor.4ctb